> Some vendors may have their own OEM group.

If a vendor has an Oem Group does an "oemUserGroups" make more sense? That would match closer with Redfish's "OemAccountype" vs just stuffing an oem user group into this userGroups?

These userGroups are documented here: 
https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/architecture/user-management.md#supported-group-roles Not clear on how Oem would work.
Since they are documented... An unexpected user group does sound like an error to me and we have done this other places. 
https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/redfish-core/lib/systems.hpp#L891

That said if we wanted to just keep going when we have an unexpected userGroup, I would be fine with that. Could look like:

        if (!getAccountTypeFromUserGroup(userGroup, accountTypes))
        {
            BMCWEB_LOG_DEBUG << "mapped value not for this userGroup value : "
                             << userGroup;
        }
I think I would prefer the current code though.

Please remove this variable and prefer to return early, as we do in other places.  also, passing in a nlohmann type makes this function less trivial than it should be.

something like:

inline std::vector<std::string> getAccountTypeFromUserGroup(group){

